## Migration Analysis

**Three patterns found** in your `EventProcessor`:

| Location | Pattern | Problem on .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call interruption | `Thread.Interrupt` won't reliably wake this |
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | Thread interruption | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable |
| `_thread.Abort()` | Forced termination | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            // GetConsumingEnumerable blocks until an item arrives
            // and throws OperationCanceledException when the token
            // is cancelled — replacing both WaitOne and Interrupt.
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — nothing to do.
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _queue.Add(item);
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();              // wakes the blocked thread cooperatively
        _thread?.Join(5000);        // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## What changed and why

1. **`ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` → `BlockingCollection<string>`** — This class combines the queue and the signaling into one thread-safe structure. `GetConsumingEnumerable` blocks until an item is available, eliminating the manual `WaitOne`/`Reset`/`Set` dance.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` / `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — The token is passed to `GetConsumingEnumerable`, which throws `OperationCanceledException` when cancelled. This cooperatively wakes the blocked thread — no forced termination needed.

3. **`IDisposable` added** — Both `CancellationTokenSource` and `BlockingCollection` are `IDisposable`. Leaking them causes timer/callback leaks.

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Race condition in original code** | The original had a bug: multiple `Enqueue` calls could `Set` the event, but only one `Dequeue` ran per `WaitOne` wakeup, losing items. `BlockingCollection` fixes this. |
| **`Handle()` isn't cancellable** | If `Handle` does long-running work, cancellation waits until it finishes. Pass `_cts.Token` into `Handle` and check it at safe points. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` mid-chain** | Only catch it at the top-level loop. Let it propagate through `Handle` so cancellation is responsive. |
| **Dispose order matters** | Call `Stop()` before `Dispose()` on the token source. Cancelling an already-disposed `CTS` throws `ObjectDisposedException`. |
